    "body": "### Problem\n\nOn Microsoft Windows, [modifyOtherKeys is enabled](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/69167006a4d3e5cfe77b9bc6e58be5dc4030fa39/src/nvim/tui/tui.c#L2410) when nvim starts but not disabled on a clean exit.\n\nI'm using ghostty version 73a93abf7 and sshing to a Windows machine and running Neovim v0.11.5. I have `TERM=xterm-256color`.\n\nIn the ghostty Terminal Inspector I see `Xterm modify keys` is true when Neovim starts. It doesn't reset to false on exit.\n\nThis causes shift-modified keys to be rendered incorrectly after exiting Neovim. If the shell is powershell nothing is rendered for a shift-modified key. If the shell is Git bash they are rendered as an ASCII sequence eg: `;2;80~` for shift+P. \n\nOther terminals:\n- iterm2: shift modifiers are fine, but control-modified keys are rendered as an ASCII sequence eg: `;5;112~` for ctrl+P.\n- foot: both shift and control-modified keys render as ASCII sequences.\n- kitty/wezterm/alacritty - no issues\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Using ghostty, ssh to a windows machine \n1. `nvim --clean`\n1. `:q`\n1. Press `shift+P`, it will be rendered as `;2;80~`  \n\n### Expected behavior\n\nOn exit, return to the default terminal mode.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.11.5\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno, vim 9.1.1914\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nWindows 11\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGhostty 73a93abf7\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nwinget",
